<section class="card">
  <h2>About Beets</h2>

  <p class="tagline">
    Reliable cool-season roots—timed by frost window, limited by fall slowdowns.
  </p>

  <p class="lede">
    Beets tolerate cool conditions and can handle light frost once established. In a typical year at the 50% probability level (1991–2020 climate normals), the key constraint isn’t survival—it’s whether roots size up before cold nights slow growth near first frost (32°F / 0°C).
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Quick Planning Reference</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Direct sow:</strong> around last frost (soil workable)</li>
    <li><strong>Days to maturity:</strong> 50–70 days (variety-dependent)</li>
    <li><strong>Frost tolerance:</strong> Light (tops can be damaged by harder freezes)</li>
  </ul>

  <p class="fine muted">
    These are practical ranges. In fall, growth rate usually matters more than “can it survive frost?”
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Spring vs Fall Timing</h2>

  <p>
    Beets work well as a spring crop and can also be a strong fall crop—if you give enough buffer for slowdowns as nights cool.
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Spring beets:</strong> early sowing into workable soil, then steady growth as temperatures rise</li>
    <li><strong>Fall beets:</strong> count backward from first frost and add buffer for late-season slowdowns</li>
  </ul>

  <p class="fine">
    If you want the core “count back from frost” logic in one place, see:
    <a href="/guides/counting-backward-from-frost-how-seed-timing-works/">Counting backward from frost: how seed timing works</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Typical GDD Requirement</h2>

  <p><strong>Base temperature:</strong> 50°F (10°C) for heat-budget comparison</p>
  <p><strong>Approximate GDD needed:</strong> ~500–800 GDD (base 50) for many beet varieties</p>

  <p>
    Beets are often constrained more by time and cool-night slowdowns than by raw heat demand, but GDD still helps describe your seasonal heat budget before first frost.
  </p>

  <p class="fine muted" style="margin-top:14px;">
    GDD = ((Daily High + Daily Low) ÷ 2) − 50
  </p>

  <div class="actions">
    <a class="button subtle" href="/tools/growing-degree-day-planner/">Use the GDD Planner</a>
  </div>

  <p class="fine">
    For how frost timing and GDD combine into a single viability model, see:
    <a href="/guides/how-frost-dates-and-growing-degree-days-work-together/">How frost dates and Growing Degree Days work together</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Minimum Frost-Free Days</h2>

  <p>
    Many beet varieties reach harvestable size in roughly <strong>50–70 days</strong>, but fall growth slows as nights cool.
    That means fall plantings often need more buffer than the label suggests.
  </p>

  <div class="actions">
    <a class="button subtle" href="/tools/frost-date-finder/">Check Your Frost-Free Season</a>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Short-Season Viability Flag</h2>

  <ul>
    <li><strong>Good choice under 100 days?</strong> Yes (reliable short-season root crop)</li>
    <li><strong>Risky under 90 days?</strong> Usually workable with variety fit + fall buffer</li>
    <li><strong>Needs season extension?</strong> Optional (light cover can preserve fall growth rate)</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>First Frost Sensitivity</h2>

  <p>
    Beet foliage can handle light frost, but harder freezes can damage tops and reduce growth rate. For frost-first planning, treat 32°F (0°C) as the boundary date and aim to size roots up with buffer ahead of that point.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Early-Maturing Strategy</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Choose faster varieties for fall timing when your frost window is short</li>
    <li>Sow early enough that roots size up before cool nights slow growth</li>
    <li>Use microclimates (full sun, wind shelter) to protect late-season heat</li>
    <li>Use light row cover in fall to preserve leaf function and extend sizing time</li>
  </ul>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Planning Model</h2>

  <p class="muted">
    Frost → Season Length → GDD → Crop Requirement → Risk Margin
  </p>

  <p>
    Beets are typically viable in short seasons because their maturity requirement is modest and they tolerate cool conditions.
    The common failure mode is insufficient buffer for fall slowdowns before first frost.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Summary</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Use 32°F (0°C) frost timing as the boundary, modeled at the 50% probability level.</li>
    <li>Beets fit short seasons well, but fall sowings need buffer for cool-night slowdowns.</li>
    <li>GDD helps describe how much seasonal heat is available before first frost.</li>
    <li>Viability improves with variety fit, sun exposure, and light fall protection when needed.</li>
  </ul>
</section>